---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="ostk docs — the OS for AI agents" description="How to install, configure, and use ostk — the local-first OS for AI agents.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Documentation</h1>

    <h2>Quick start</h2>
    <pre><code># Install
curl -fsSL https://ostk.ai/install | sh

# Boot the OS on a repo
cd your-repo
ostk boot

# The OS is running. Agents use their normal tools.
# The bash shim intercepts commands and adds coordination.</code></pre>

    <p>After boot, the OS:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Tracks every file write with generation counters</li>
      <li>Resolves conflicts between concurrent agents (Hot PR)</li>
      <li>Compresses shell output to save tokens</li>
      <li>Maintains an audit trail of every action</li>
    </ul>
    <p>No configuration needed. No <code>.ostk.yml</code>. The OS reads the repo and orients.</p>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>
    <img src="/diagrams/architecture-overview.svg" alt="ostk architecture: tools, squasher, kernel, and FCP drivers" class="diagram" />
    <p>ostk has two layers:</p>

    <h3>the kernel</h3>
    <p>A single Rust binary. Provides:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Process table and PTY supervision</li>
      <li>Filesystem with optimistic concurrency control</li>
      <li>Hot PR conflict resolution (4 tiers: auto-merge, assisted, manual rebase, diagnostic)</li>
      <li>Generation table for file versioning</li>
      <li>Agent identity and heartbeat</li>
      <li>Output compression (VTE strip + dedup)
        <img src="/diagrams/compression-pipeline.svg" alt="Compression pipeline: raw output to compressed with 80% token savings" class="diagram diagram-wide" />
      </li>
      <li>MCP server (<code>ostk serve</code>) exposing the full tool surface</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>fcp-* (device drivers)</h3>
    <p>Domain intelligence plugins:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>fcp-rust: Rust analyzer integration</li>
      <li>fcp-python: Python LSP integration</li>
      <li>fcp-drawio: Diagram reasoning</li>
      <li>More as needed. Each driver speaks the domain's native language.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The kernel provides primitives. Device drivers provide intelligence.</p>

    <h2 id="tack-grammar">Tack grammar</h2>
    <p>Tack is the intent-capture language. You type shorthand. The OS compiles it.</p>
    <pre><code>:command object              # Basic command
:verb1 :verb2 :verb3         # Chain commands (sequential)
.p0 .p1 .p2                  # Priority shorthand
-&gt; flow                      # Sequence operator</code></pre>

    <p>Examples:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>You type</th><th>What happens</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>:compile</code></td><td>Unstructured thinking becomes executable needles</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>:compile :plan :ship</code></td><td>Compile, plan the work, commit</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>:hs add issue "fix auth" .p0</code></td><td>File a P0 needle</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>:calibrate</code></td><td>Retrospective on a thread</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Tack is not a fixed grammar. The OS learns your shorthand over sessions. What you type today becomes vocabulary tomorrow.</p>

    <h2>Key commands</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Command</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>ostk boot</code></td><td>Load state from <code>.haystack/boot.md</code>, report</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk needle add</code></td><td>File a new needle (executable work item)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk verify</code></td><td>Run verification against needle criteria</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk commit</code></td><td>Commit with audit trail</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk bench</code></td><td>Run benchmark scenarios</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk ps</code></td><td>Show agent process table</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk nudge</code></td><td>Send a notification to an agent or human</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk serve</code></td><td>Start the MCP server</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk audit</code></td><td>Query the audit trail</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk should</code></td><td>File bugs and features in natural language</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk tui</code></td><td>Terminal interface for real-time OS monitoring</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>ostk mcp call</code></td><td>Proxy an external MCP server through the kernel</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>MCP proxy</h2>
    <p>Proxy external MCP servers through the kernel. Any MCP-compatible server becomes available to agents running under the OS.</p>
    <pre><code>ostk mcp call &lt;server&gt; &lt;tool&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>The kernel handles routing, authentication, and audit logging for all proxied MCP calls.</p>

    <h2>TUI</h2>
    <p>Terminal interface for real-time OS monitoring. See agent processes, file writes, and audit events as they happen.</p>
    <pre><code>ostk tui</code></pre>

    <h2>Semantic compression</h2>
    <p>Embeddings-powered deduplication saves more tokens by detecting semantically similar output, not just identical lines.</p>
    <pre><code># Enable with the embeddings feature flag
cargo build --features embeddings</code></pre>

    <h2>ostk should</h2>
    <p>File bugs and features in natural language. The OS compiles your intent into structured needles.</p>
    <pre><code>ostk should "fix the auth flow when tokens expire"
ostk should "add retry logic to the API client"</code></pre>

    <h2>Downloads</h2>
    <p>Latest release: <strong>v1.5.1</strong> — MCP proxy, TUI, semantic compression, 871+ tests.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/releases/tag/v1.5.1" onclick="plausible('Download', {props: {target: 'release-page'}})">ostk v1.5.1 release</a> — macOS arm64/x86_64, Linux musl arm64/x86_64, GPG .asc signatures</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Or install via script (always fetches latest): <a href="https://ostk.ai/install" onclick="plausible('Install', {props: {method: 'curl'}})">view install script</a></p>
    <pre><code>curl -fsSL https://ostk.ai/install | sh</code></pre>

    <h2>Governance</h2>
    <img src="/diagrams/file-governance.svg" alt="File governance: OSfile, HUMANFILE, Agentfile, ENTITYFILE" class="diagram" />
    <p>ostk uses a layered governance model. Each layer is a signed file that defines authority, preferences, and behavior.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/docs/humanfile">HUMANFILE</a> — operator identity, tack dialect, preferences. GPG-signed by the human.</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/entityfile">ENTITYFILE</a> — instance governance. Defines trust tiers, authority chain, kernel attestation.</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/agentfile">Agentfile</a> — agent process descriptor. FROM, BOOT, TOOL, LIMIT, WORK directives.</li>
      <li><a href="/docs/osfile">OSfile</a> — OS identity carrier. The signed binary + primefile = OS identity.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Further reading</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/bench">needle-bench: benchmarking agents</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/releases/tag/v1.5.1">v1.5.1 release notes</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/os-tack">Find us</a></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Base>
